  "enhanced_information": "Methylphenidate is the drug of choice for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), as it is a central nervous system stimulant that effectively increases attention span and reduces impulsivity, aligning with clinical guidelines that recommend stimulant medications as first-line treatments. Haloperidol, an antipsychotic, is not typically used for ADHD and may complicate its management. Imipramine, a tricyclic antidepressant, is not considered a first-line treatment for ADHD. Alprazolam, a benzodiazepine, is also not indicated for ADHD and may complicate its symptoms. Therefore, the consensus supports methylphenidate as the preferred choice for ADHD management."
